&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Our version is closely based on your C++ sources and the great
&gt;&gt; Simmerson&#39;s Java version. But our approach was a modular one. Well,
&gt;&gt; any OOP based version is modular enough, but we&#39;ve tried to separate
&gt;&gt; the concept of the experiment from the main code, meaning that you
&gt;&gt; basically need to import the libraries, specify the config parameters
&gt;&gt; and write a fitness function.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Although everything seems to be working (including the XOR example),
&gt;&gt; it&#39;s not &quot;officially&quot; released since I need to finish the FAQ and add
&gt;&gt; a basic tutorial. But it&#39;s rather simple to checkout from the SVN
&gt;&gt; repository and play with the XOR example. The only requirement is
&gt;&gt; Python 2.5 (you still need some other libraries in order to plot the
&gt;&gt; results).
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; The NEAT-Python project URL is: http://code.google.com/p/neat-python
&gt;&gt; (licensed under GPLv3)
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; The name &quot;NEAT-Python&quot; is not a a very good one, I&#39;d really like to
&gt;&gt; have something similar to PyNEAT, but that&#39;s already taken.
&gt;&gt; Suggestions are welcome!
&gt;&gt;
